node.text:
Thanks to our fantastic sponsor: @matific I am sharing essential tips for teachers to prepare for the school year! Feel free to share or ask questions and add your own tips in the comments section. For more tips, be sure to check out my new blog post in which I share additional information and ideas that will help us all start the year calm and ready to go! ~ Jen
.
.

node.text:
Just think, a term ago I was excitedly showing you all my classroom! For those of you interested in a possible new enrolment in early learning at this lovely school @st_petersanglican there is an information session on at 1:30 tomorrow (Thursday). Register on the website for the virtual event. The link is also in stories on @invite_to_learn 😘

Now, about my class: I miss them terribly but am very thankful for Zoom. We are currently focusing on questions and sharing our wonderings. The parents of my students are incredible and are doing amazing things at home. I keep telling myself it’s not forever. If you have any advice, fun Zoom ideas, great online resources, I’m always open to reading more. I am not perfect, and am as much a learner as anyone, including my students.💕 Jen @living_future_memories

I’m thinking these cubes would be awesome in sensory play too. Oobleck, slime, play dough or just water??? What do you think? ~ ❤️ Jen @living_future_memories

Butterfly love🦋 Easy, fun & inexpensive are always a winner! I especially love when a fun art process becomes not only a beautiful product but is also something that can be used later in play. This is a great example!

1️⃣Colour paper towel with washable markers.
2️⃣Spray with water and leave to dry.
3️⃣Gather middle of the paper towel and clip with a peg to make a butterfly.

This could be a great provocation with older grades to discuss symmetry, or for younger grades patterns, or environments in which animals live, adaptation, change etc. It can be a stand alone activity, sure, but I love it when things like this can lead into discussion & further learning/questioning/curiosity. This was first posted on @invite_to_learn ~Jen x @living_future_memories @where_heart_meets_home

Have I ever inspired you? Perhaps to try something new, make small changes, or big ones! Please, please comment to let me know. Today I could really use the encouragement. We all need it from time to time. If you like what you see on someone else’s post, maybe write something today.❤️ In return I’ve posted some favourites for you.😘😘

1️⃣Changing the shelf invites interest. We are wired to be curious about change/novelty.
2️⃣Lego/duplo geoboard.
3️⃣Nature paint brushes. Use paper tape to attach.
4️⃣Frozen paint on pop sticks. Paper in a tray is really helpful here.
5️⃣The go-to dining room shelf.
6️⃣Masking/paper/painters tape with markers- helps to learn about writing on lines.
7️⃣Number bead threading on pipe cleaners (number beans!)
8️⃣Rock and magnet patterns on a chalk board.
9️⃣Letters and numbers on leaves. Very inexpensive resource!
🔟Catalogue cutting! Children love choosing things to cut and glue.

Tuff tray love❤️ I’m constantly asked where I purchased my black tray or the school tuff tray. Both places no longer stock them. BUT I noticed that @thecreativetoyshop DO sell them now, which is awesome. I’m just about to place an order for Libby’s birthday (it’s Wednesday, so I’m pushing it I know🙈😬) and it made me think to share this. I’ve added a few of my fav tuff tray ideas, both for those who are cool with the mess and those who aren’t into it. All of these ideas were really popular, and I hope it helps a few of you.😘 

The upside down bath mat (from @kmartaus - very inexpensive) is awesome. Using it with a dropper and jars of coloured water is also great. Put some paper underneath and an art work is created at the same time.😊

For all of you who have reached out during this time of lockdown for my family and I - thank you!! I’m not going to pretend working full time (1 day onsite, 4 from home- really 6 days as one of the parents from school said in an email to me❤️) with 5 of my children involved in remote learning, and a Hubby who works shift work at a hospital, is easy. It’s not. But I’m looking for the good in every day, am soaking up every opportunity to connect with students at school (I miss them all so much😢), and have organised well with a good rhythm at home, so it is working for now. I just have very little down time or sleep.😂 All the children in my care are worth every single second & I hope I can be someone who makes this time a little bit better. It’s in the dark times we need to be the light.✨

Now, where are you on the messy play continuum??! All-the-mess-all-the-time, mess-within-reason, occasionally-messy, once-in-awhile-messy, easy-clean-up-only, never-messy-play. There is nothing wrong with any of these! Families enjoying their time together is best.❤️ Jen @living_future_memories

Answering FAQs + A quick look back over old videos to relax (they make me happy!) ❤️ Because I’m struggling to get to sleep after focusing on work too long today. 

FAQ:
Q: How old are your students?
A: 3-5yrs (4 by April, and none over 5 in January when we start)
Q: Where is your school?
A: Sydney, Australia 
Q: Can my child be in your class?!
A: 😂🥰 (Asked alllll the time!) My class is full but a new Prep class has just been opened. Contact @st_petersanglican for info. I’ve met a few fans along the way.❤️
Q: What kind of school is it?
A: An International Baccalaureate school.
Q: Where are all your resources from?
A: Lots are school items. Some are mine. Businesses I love are @thecreativetoyshop @modernteaching @cleverpatch @learnandgrow_toys @honeybeetoys @growing.kind and even @kmartaus and @targetaus for some things like baskets and mats. There are more! Check out tags on my posts.
Q: Can I work with you?!
A: Yes! There are a few positions available at the moment from bus driver to music & PE specialists (due to extra bus route, people moving away & pregnancy 💞). I’ll link the application in stories.😘
Q: What do you do if they all want the same activity?
A: Students ask me to set a 5 minute timer on my Apple Watch. It works for two reasons: those waiting have a limited wait time & it gives warning to those involved in play. 
Q: How do you keep your classroom clean?
A: awesome cleaners.💞 AND I ring a bell and ask students to “make OUR classroom BEAUTIFUL.” Language is important- as is cleaning with them and giving them specific clean up tasks. Remember kids need a regular rhythm to the day and know what is expected. 
.
.
What other questions do you have for me?? I especially LOVED the mirror painting. I think there is a reel somewhere on my feed for it.😍 ~ Jen

Whole table drawing when A4 paper is all you have. Masking (paper or painters) tape sticky side up, stuck to the edges of the table with extra pieces of the tape. 

Great things about this:
❤️Big arm movements are possible, with lots of freedom to create.
❤️Many children can draw together at once.
❤️Can be lifted off table for meals and placed back for continuing creating later.
❤️Stays perfectly in place (no falling on the floor and tears).

Ideas:
💙Crayons (or crayons with watercolour)
💙Pencils (alone or with crayons)
💙Markers (can add water spray bottles after- check markers are washable!)
💙Paint (start with a few drawn shapes as a hook for interest)
💙Collage 

Shares/questions welcome- just make sure you give my 15 yr old daughter credit 😉 It was her brilliant idea as I was out for a run, my 8 yr old Daisy wanted to do table drawing, and Izzy didn’t know where our roll of brown paper had been placed. This is a perfect example of why it’s important to teach our children to think for themselves! Problem solving is a life skill. Thank you Isabel for this great idea!!

R E M E M B E R ❤️ My guiding thoughts. When I am with children here is some of what I always try to keep in mind:

1) Children are people. I aim to treat them the way I want to be treated.
2) Everyone wants to know FIRST that I like them. Respect, openness and a willingness to listen follows.
3) A smile does not cost a cent. Not. One. Cent.
4) Fair is not equal. Fair is making sure everyone has what they need. Help them to understand we are all better when we help people who need more help.
4) Bring the calm, don’t join the chaos. Rhythms of the day matter.
5) Have FUN. There is enough boredom.
6) Loud is not bad. But quiet & rest are sometimes needed too. Lead the way into rest with books when the loud is too much.
7) Bad days happen to us all. Them & me. Acknowledge, shrug it off, & start the next day fresh.
8) Grudges are unnecessary. Be more kind than seems necessary.
9) Progress is always possible. Perfect is impossible.
10) Time and resources are mouldable. Be flexible with both.
11) Be creative. Remember the childlike freedom of creating without feeling the end result matters.
12) When it’s hard, I remember: they have only been ALIVE ___years. They are still learning how to be here.
13) I’m completely flawed. We all have issues. Children just aren’t as practiced at hiding their problems.
14) Join their wonder. Let curiosity be not only okay but a worthwhile pursuit.
15) The WHY always matters. Always. Explain the why of what will be done. They want to know even if they don’t ask. I wouldn’t want to do something irrelevant, so why should they?
16) We all have feelings. Be open to them all, helping children find their way through the hard parts. Talk later after big emotions have passed, as this helps to navigate future feelings.
17) Ask for help when needed. Professionals have their jobs for a reason. I have limits.
18) I’m making history. I’m part of someone’s history. Make my part worthy.
19) Let them see me authentically: mistakes, sometimes messy writing, and things that hold my interest and heart. Show them that learning never ends through my desire to learn always.
20) I am a role model. I ask myself: would I want them to be me right now?

Jen❤️

2 ingredients (3 if you want it coloured) AND I make it in the bag I store it in (I haven’t had much success with storing doughs in my jars😕). One key to keeping doughs longer: ALWAYS play with it with freshly washed hands.💁‍♀️
